            <bug_when>2009-09-23 10:49:15 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>I currently work with a few newbies to JavaScript, Python, etc. For them it seems to be quite illogical that documentation files, which may be also useful when browsing the class files are named &quot;__init__.js&quot;. I know I already came up with such a change request a few months ago, but IMHO there was no bug added for this.

The change itself could be somewhat solved in a compatible way as it might be easy to support both file names for some time.

My suggestion is to rename &quot;__init__.js&quot; files to &quot;packagedoc.txt&quot;. I would also like to remove the need to encapsulate the content of the documentation in JS comments then. When you really want to write an overview of features of a specific namespace it might be a useful enhancement to not force users to keep it the same style as in JS classes. One also not need the intelli-tips of the IDEs here as there are no params, throws or returns in packages.

Instead of writing:

/**
 * My probably lenghty package documentation
 *
 */

one simply writes:

My probably lenghty package documentation</thetext>
          </long_desc>
